'''Dialects of Pars''' are a group of southwestern and northwestern Iranian dialects spoken in the central [[Fars Province|Pars]] province. The southwestern dialects can be divided into three families of dialects according to geographical distribution and local names: Southwestern (''[[Lori dialects|Lori]]''), South-central ([[Kuhmareyi language|Kuhmareyi]]) and Southeastern (''[[Larestani dialects|Larestani]]'').<ref name="Iranica1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/fars-viii |title=FĀRS viii. Dialects |author=Windfuhr, Gernot |date=15 December 1999 |work=Encyclopaedia Iranica Online |publisher=Columbia University |location=New York |accessdate=2010-05-23 |quote=The Fārs dialects proper used to be locally referred to as Tājīkī in the sense of the Iranian-speaking settled, non-tribal populations...}}</ref><ref name="Iranica2">{{Cite web|author=SWindfuhr, Gernot |title=FARROḴZĀD,FORŪḠ-ZAMĀN |url=http://www.iranica.com/newsite/articles/v9f3/v9f393c.html#viii |work=Encyclopædia Iranica |publisher=Columbia University |location=New York |accessdate=2009-04-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090115212937/http://www.iranica.com/newsite/articles/v9f3/v9f393c.html |archivedate=15 January 2009 }}</ref> Under [[linguistic typology]] a part of the dialects of the region can be classified as follows:<ref name="salami2004">Salami, A., 1383 [[Iranian calendar|AP]] / 2004 [[Gregorian calendar|AD]]. Ganjineye guyeššenâsiye Fârs (The treasury of the dialectology of Fars). First Volume, [[Academy of Persian Language and Literature]]. [http://persianacademy.ir/fa/ganjifars01.aspx] {{ISBN|964-7531-32-X}} {{fa icon}}</ref><ref name="salami2005">Salami, A., 1384 [[Iranian calendar|AP]] / 2005 [[Gregorian calendar|AD]]. Ganjineye guyeššenâsiye Fârs (The treasury of the dialectology of Fars). Second Volume, The academy of Persian language and literature. [http://persianacademy.ir/fa/ganjifars02.aspx] {{ISBN|964-7531-39-7}} {{fa icon}}</ref><ref name="salami2006">Salami, A., 1385 [[Iranian calendar|AP]] / 2006 [[Gregorian calendar|AD]]. Ganjineye guyeššenâsiye Fârs (The treasury of the dialectology of Fars). Third Volume, The academy of Persian language and literature. [http://persianacademy.ir/fa/ganjifars03.aspx] {{ISBN|964-7531-54-0}} {{fa icon}}</ref><ref name="salami2007">Salami, A., 1386 [[Iranian calendar|AP]] / 2007 [[Gregorian calendar|AD]]. Ganjineye guyeššenâsiye Fârs (The treasury of the dialectology of Fars). Fourth Volume, The academy of Persian language and literature. [http://persianacademy.ir/fa/s1504871.aspx] ISBN 978-964--7531-73-3 {{fa icon}}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" style="font-size:100%; text-align:center; width:80%" |- ! colspan="2" | [[Southwestern Iranian languages|Southwestern]] ! [[Northwestern Iranian languages|Northwestern]] |- | style="font-weight: bold;" | [[Nominative–accusative language|Nominative–accusative]] | style="font-weight: bold;" | [[Split ergativity|Split-Ergative]] in past transitive constructions |- | Tajiki Kalani, Lori Kalani, Mamassani Lori, Balyani, Hayati(Dowlat Abadi), Lordarengani, Dezhgahi/Gowri, Richi, Tang Kishi, Zakhoruyei |'''[[Kuhmareyi language|Kuhmareyi]]''': [[Davani dialect|Davani]], Dahlei, Kandeyi, Kuzargi, Masarmi, Birovakani, Dadenjani, Dorounaki/Mehboudi, Banafi, Papuni, Dusirani, Somghani, Gorganayi-Gavkoshaki, Mosqani, Nudani; '''[[Larestani language|Larestani]]''': Asiri, Aheli, Khonji, Gerrashi/Zeynal Abadi, Kalati (Evaz), Kariyani; Others: Shurabi |style="border-top:0px;" valign="top" | [[Koroshi dialect|Koroshi]], [[Sivandi language|Sivandi]], [[Abduyi dialect|Abduyi]], [[Korouni dialect|Korouni]] |- |}
And the extinct [[Kazeruni dialect (old)|old Kazeruni]] and Old Shirazi (Sherazi) dialects. This group of dialects is not to be confused with the standard [[Persian language|Persian]], the official language of Iran; and they are not restricted to the present border of Fars province.<ref name="Iranica2" /><ref name="payne1987">{{Cite book| title=The World's Major Languages | year=1987 | last=Payne | first=J.R. | editor=Bernard Comrie | publisher=Oxford University Press | location=Oxford | isbn=978-0-19-506511-4 | page=514 }}</ref>
