{{Infobox language |name=Fe'fe' |altname=Nufi, Fotouni, Bafang<ref>[http://www.language-archives.org/language/fmp OLAC resources in and about the Fe'fe' language]. Open Language Archives.</ref> |nativename=Fe'efe'e |states =[[Cameroon]] |region=[[Haut-Nkam]] (Upper Nkam) |ethnicity=[[Bamileke people|Bamileke Fe'efe'e]] |speakers=c. 140,000 |date=2005 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo]] |fam4=[[Southern Bantoid]] |fam5=[[Grassfields languages|Grassfields]] |fam6=[[Eastern Grassfields languages|Eastern]] |fam7=[[Bamileke languages|Bamileke]] |script=[[Latin script|Latin]] |iso3=fmp |glotto=fefe1239 |glottorefname=Fe'fe' }}
'''Fe'fe'''' or '''Fe'efe'e''', also known as ''Nufi'' and ''Bafang'', is a [[Bamileke language]] spoken in [[Cameroon]], around the town of [[Bafang]]. It was one of the four languages selected for ''option'' at the [[Collège Libermann at Douala]] (along with [[Duala language|Duala]], [[Basaa language|Basaa]] and [[Banjun language|Banjun]]).<ref>Patrick Renaud, ''Le Français au Cameroun'' in: ''Le Français hors de France'' sous la direction de A. Valdman, Editions Honoré Champion, Paris, 1979.</ref>
